svc_norm_2factor.r

jflournoy

Thu Aug 13 18:36:15 2015

This is an EFA for the ratings of the self on all items. Only 70 of the 77 have totally complete data, and to be conservative, I’m just looking at those 70. We don’t lose too much without those 7 and it’s easier to satisfy assumptions of EFA without missing data. Haven’t looked closely at what they’re missing yet though.

Descriptives

These histograms by themselves tell a really interesting story – you can see that there is a some overlap between Acc and Cont ratings, but some items distinguish between them. These line up with a lot of our a priori ideas – see anger and jealousy. Pretty cool.

Aside from the status items, you also can see the scores on depression and substance use, among other things. Keep in mind the middle 2 CES_D items are reverse coded. SES ladder is mostly between 3-7 on a 9 point scale.

The plot below seems to indicate that a good number of people consider themselves high status in both ways (all responses in the top right quadrant). There doesn’t seem to be perfect separation between the two. However, note that the bottom left quadrant reflects responses from people that think neither type of status describes them well (31 people). Also note that the overlap group is only comprises 13 people. Number of primarily accepted status = 39, and primarily controversial status participants = 15.

Self Ratings

Best predictors of status

First thing, let’s see what items are best at predicting status using regularized regression for multinomial responses. This uses cross validation to give us the set of predictors that leads to the best out-of-sample prediction (least error). We probably want these in our set of final items.

The first plot shows how prediction error varies as a function of the number of parameters in the model, and how much weight each gets (the size of the coefficient).

The second set of plots actually show the size of each coefficient predicting both types of status as the constraint parameter, lambda, is tightened (left-to-right).

This table shows all the non-zero coefficients.

If we were merely trying to predict status from a future data set containing these same items, the above table would be the best subset to use.

While we’re interested in predicting status, we’re not actually asking about status. Rather, we’re asking about traits that we think relate to status. So while the above set of items might tell us who is likely to have one or the other kind of status, in the context of an fMRI analysis it would be hard to argue that activity observed during self evaluation of these traits is some measure of status-related brain activity.

EFA to look at latent constructs

The more traditional approach would be to use EFA. What we hope to get is 2 factors the correspond to Accepted High Status and Controversial High Status.

However, the scree plot shows very clearly a 4 factor solution will account for most of the variance, with no real gain if we increase beyond 4. Ignoring that, we want the best 2 factor solution so that we can run reasonable contrasts between these two sets. We can think of them as super-factors, perhaps.

Here’s the raw output, if you like, but see below for a prettier table. Notice the factors are allowed to (anti) correlate.

These factors are pretty interpretable, if you ask me.

  1. First (PA1), is surgency/dynamism/extraversion: Popular; not depressed, lonely, or insecure; trendy, confident, popular, social. Daring and adventurous.
  2. Third (PA2), we have…aggression (reversed, ’cause EFA)? Rude, mean, bossy, snobby, as well as lazy and fake, not sympathetic, not trustworthy.

I think this plot is supposed to show how much separation we get – not bad actually.

These clusters of items may still be related to status (and they’re actually pretty close to the expected factors). We can correlate self rated accepted and controversial status with the factor scores to start exploring this.

Correlations

In the output below, SelfPop_1 is controversial, and SelfPop_2 is accepted.

Also:

  1. ‘Admired’ (PA1; named after its first item)
  2. ‘Aggressive’ (PA2)

We see that controversial status is correlated with ‘Aggressive’.

Accepted status is highly correlated with ‘Admired’.

Grain of salt: No correction for multiple comparison here.

Slightly bigger grain of salt: 8 folks are missing a rating on a couple items here and there, so I impute the mean so we can get predicted factor scores. This means that significance values and CIs close to threshold below should be treated lightly (but it doesn’t change things too much).

This gets more interesting in the regressions.

What has EFA told us?

Well, we have four factors that we’ve forced into 2 that are helpfully related to self reported status. This is what we want.

EFA using machine learning to select items

Now we need a principled way to select items. We could use some communality cutoff, or loading strength. But we know we want 48 items, so let’s start there. We can use regularized regression methods to let the machine learn what 48 items (or 50 so we can drop a couple if they’re a little out of balance) give us the best set of factors. We can then compare that to the EFA results as well as to the earlier classification.

Based on this table, we could drop items with low scores on ‘crit’, which is just an average of Z scores for each of our criteria (main factor loading, cross-loadings, and communality). This way is is more of an art than a mathematical method, so….

I’m going to set this route aside for now, because the SPCA is made for item selection, especially if we get good prediction below. (The basis behind SPCA is the same as PCA/EFA, which is is to identify loadings on factors that capture the maximum amount of variance in the data. In light of that, the 48 items should do what we want).

The Aggressive scale, predicts Controversial High Status, and holding it constant, the Admired scale also predicts Controversial status, though less strongly. The Admired scale predicts Accepted High Status.

A Little CFA

Grain of salt: We don’t think this should actually reflect the constructs in our data – we know there are probably actually 4 factors, but this tells us how things look if we were to really go for this model. It is not the worst I’ve ever seen!

What conclusions can we draw? The CFA indicates that we could do better in this model. But the scale alphas coefficients are very good. However, there are a lot of cross loadings in the EFA, and we totally ignore those, which is why the CFA fit is so shabby. This can especially be the case with many items per scale.

Next Steps

This is pretty good to go I think, conditional on your feedback. However, it will be important to check this all in the ratings of a typical Controversial and Accepted High Status target. This is the plan:

  1. For each participant’s rating of each type of High Status teen we can get scores on the scales we just created, and then take a mean across those ratings.
    • We would expect to see that people think that a typical Controversial High Status target is high on the Aggressive scale, and maybe somewhat high on the Admired scale.
    • We’d also expect that Accepted High status targets are rated high on the ‘Admired’ scale.

  2. For each scale (and even each item), I want to know how much agreement there is among raters on how well it describes these two types of targets.

  3. Finally, we have data on depression and substance use, but both sets of items need to be modeled as coming from a different-than-normal distribution (substance use especially).

Here’s a preview of status-type analysis in the meantime. I’m less certain of this approach in general, and very happy for any guidance.

Status-type ratings

Now we can use the data about what people think is characteristic of the two status types to figure out what best classifies the two types. Hopefully we’ll get good overlap with the above items.

The EFA below tells a slightly different story than above, but there are a lot of cross loadings, and I don’t know whether I should trust this method entirely on this type of data. This is a really well fitting EFA, though.

Another approach: Using glmnet, we can get a good set of cross-validated classifying features – in our case, adjectives.

These are the items that give have the most information for classification of the type of status. These should be the items that show the biggest differences between accepted and controversial ratings. Hopefully, they all show up in our factor analyses above, too.
